#1760

XANTE ANNOUNCES THE FIRST HIGH RESOLUTION LASER PRINTER
WITH ADOBE PostScript FOR THE JAPANESE MARKET

MOBILE, Ala.- Feb. 20, 1995 - Xante Corporation introduces the Accel-a-
Writer 8200J, a Japanese version of the Accel-a-Writer 8200 which was
recently named Best new Monochrome Printer of the Year by MacUser
Magazine. This printer becomes the only 1200 x 1200 dpi, Adope
PostScript laser printer available in the Japanese market. The Accel-a-
Writer 8200J can be configured with either seven or fifteen Japanese
fonts which have been licensed from Morisawa and Company, Ltd.

Based on Canon's 16 page-per-minute LBP-BXII laser print engine, the
Accel-a-Writer 8200J is capable of printing full bleed 11" x 17"/A3
documents as well as oversized pages up to 12" x 25". The Accel-a-Writer
8200J ships standard with 48 MB RAM, upgradeable to 64 MB, and it
includes a high speed controller built around the AMD 29030/33 MHz RISC
processor. In addition to 1200 x 1200 dpi, this printer supports a
600 x 600 dpi draft mode.
info: tel. 334/476-8189
------------------------------------------------------------------------
#1761

NEC TECHNOLOGIES MAKES AGGRESSIVE BID FOR CORPORATE
DESKTOP MARKET WITH PowerMate V and VP SERIES

SAN JOSE, Calif. - Feb. 20, 1995 - NEC Technologies Inc. today
announced its PowerMate V and VP value-based desktop systems,
a new family of Intel 486 and Pentium processor-based systems
for general office and corporate use.

By incorporating advanced technology such as a PCI architecture and
Desktop Management Interface (DMI) compliance, the PowerMate V and VP
Series provide the performance, productivity features and configuration
flexibility required by today's budget conscious corporate environment.
info: tel. 408/433-2127 or E-mail: rfarana@nectech.com
------------------------------------------------------------------------
#1762

INNOVATIVE SPARCstation VOYAGER FROM SUN
NOW COSTS LESS, HAS MORE STORAGE

MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. - Feb. 21, 1995 - Sun Microsystems Computer
Company (SMCC) today introduced two additions to its pioneering
SPARCstation Voyager family of portable workstations -- offering
three times the base memory and more than twice the hard disk of
previous configurations at a lower cost. Industry reductions in the
cost of flat panel displays and SMCC's volume business model have
combined to decrease the cost of existing SPARCstation Voyager
workstation configurations by up to 30 percent.

The new SPARCstation Voyager features 48 megabytes of RAM and an 810-
megabyte hard disk to address customer requests for a more powerful
portable computer.
------------------------------------------------------------------------
